  "text": "Monocytes have receptors for AII and respond to the ligand with increased lipid oxidation and uptake, as well as augmentation of their immune functions such as stimulation of MCP-1. [CITATION_1] 27 The current studies show that AII also has direct effects on macrophage migration. Thus, MCP-1 significantly increased migration of macrophages from both salineexposed and AII-exposed mice. However, the migratory response was significantly greater in macrophages from the AII-exposed versus saline-exposed mice. The finding that AII strongly potentiates the chemotactic response was further solidified in experiments in macrophages harvested from AGTR1-deficient mice. As expected, macrophage migration was not different between AII-infused and saline-infused AGTR-1-deficient mice. As in the wild-type mice, MCP-1 still increased the migratory response in macrophages from AGTR-1 mice. However, contrasting the result in wild-type mice, the increased chemotaxis in response to MCP-1 was unaltered by in vivo exposure to AII. The current studies of effects of in vivo exposure to AII on macrophage function recapitulate previous in vitro findings, which showed greater migration in association with phosphorylation of 2 cytoskeletal proteins, proline-rich tyrosine kinase 2, and paxillin, after exposure to AII. 28 Cumulatively, these studies show that AII potentiates macrophage migration and that this response is mediated by the AGTR-1 on the macrophage.",
